ic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, Kieran.","English (Lancashire, of Norman origin): nickname for a man with a moustache, from Old French <i>gernon</i>, <i>grenon</i> ‘moustache’.","Irish (Offaly, Westmeath and Down): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Grianáin</b> (see   Greenan  )."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Gernon was born about 1314, in Essex, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir John de Gernon, was 28 and her mother, Alice de Coleville, was 34. She had at least 1 son with Geoffrey Gresley. She died about 1352, in Burton upon Trent St Modwen, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 40."},"et":{"Abt 1314–Abt 1352":"umbes 1314–umbes 1352","1314–1352":"1314–1352","1298–1331":"1298–1331","1328–1395":"1328–1395","1287–1332":"1287–1332","1282–1334":"1282–1334","liv 1330":"1330","1352":"1352","Abt 1314":"umbes 1314","1395":"1395","1282":"1282","1314":"1314","28 February 1334":"28. veebruar 1334","1334":"1334","1332":"1332","1331":"1331","Abt 1352":"umbes 1352","1287":"1287","1298":"1298","from 1 April 1332 to 28 March 1334":"1. aprill 1332 kuni 28. märts 1334","1328":"1328","Of Leeys Manor, , Essex, England":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bakewell, Derbyshire, England":"Bakewell, Derbyshire, England","of Lamington, nr Oxford, Eng.":"Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Drakelow, Burton-Upon-Trent, Derbyshire, England":"Burton upon Trent St Modwen, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Morton, Derbyshire, England":"Morton, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1314–Abt 1352":"noin 1314–noin 1352","1314–1352":"1314–1352","1298